	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Dwedit wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Color #0 is transparent, so with the sprite drawn behind the background, the sprite will still show through any transparent pixels in the background.</div>
<br />
<br />Thanks for the quick reply!  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> 
<br />So does this mean color #0 is always transparent no matter what color we have set in the current pallette? I mean If I have used some other color as color #1 in the pallette (the one which the sky uses) would it still be transparent?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Bregalad</b> [ Fri Nov 20, 2009 3:54 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The color #0 of tiles is always the transparent one, and that for both BG and sprites. The color you write at $3f00 or $3f10 is the one you see when both BG and sprites have a transparent pixel.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Fri Nov 20, 2009 7:47 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><strong>If you want some concept of "behind the sky":</strong> Put a gray <a href="http://www.neogaf.com/forum/showpost.php?p=9490699&amp;postcount=70" class="postlink">cloud-bush</a> in the sky, and the sprite can appear behind the cloud.
<br />
<br /><strong>If you want to hide a sprite entirely:</strong> Set its Y coordinate to any value in the range $EF through $FF.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
